So Quintilian says the creditor cannot go to the ειη-θὴν, salvo pudore, except the debtor fails him. And in this sense pudor is often conjoined with justice, as in Ovid. So Hesiod conj0ins δίκη and αἰδὼς. And Plato says that αῖδώς is the assessor of δίκη. And in the Protagoras, he says that the two, δίκη and αἶδώς, a feeling of justice and of mutual reverence, were given to man to hold society together.
